One thing Leibniz says is that "symmetry extends into the unknown", e.g. if there is symmetry between the visible parts of two things, then there will also be symmetry in their invisible parts too. This is how metaphysics sorta works I guess. Surprisingly an applicable principle.

An example is when you read scientific articles that say: "X bacteria has been associated with a lack of autoimmune disease" and when you read what seems to increase the bacteria it's always the old sun exposure, B-vitamins, kefir type bullshit. It always works even if invisible.

I think you can extend it to "if you work with what you know, you also work with what you don't know", which is why Rene Guenon said a treatise on grammar is also necessarily a metaphysical text or the "liberal arts" took on initiatory symbolism under Dante Alighieri type guys...

Fr. Stephen De Young mentioned how husband and wife only partially reveal themselves to each other, day to day. Baron Julius Evola wrote how the regal Roman pater expressed himself through symbols and signs, in the rites he performed. His family regarded him as almost immaterial.

The stoicism of our own grandfathers is an echo of this. Hiding all emotions, worries, fears, refusing to admit one is in pain during disease or ever call an ambulance. Showing these human weaknesses takes down the edifice with its facade, the omnipotent godhead of the household.

Everything in woman is a riddle and its solution is pregnancy, says Mr. Nietzsche, but the secret of paternity lies only in the grave. There is no getting off this Evangelion, no breaks, except for coffee. It's why whining as a father is almost punishable with death. A wild ride.

Mr. Tate saying you should always tell women you have "something to do" at midnight instead of admitting that you're going to sleep, a friend here saying you should text a foid you love only after nightfall, all of these are contemporary example of the eternal theatre of romance.

Dr. Giulio Evola describes a king and queen living apart in their castle bedrooms, without seeing each other for weeks, and only meeting to make love in the dark between absences. Lovers deciphering each other's pheromones, like counter-intelligence officers above sheets of code.

But the radical opposite to this, absolute acceptance of the other's openness, a luminous clarity of seeing everything real, is no less valid, even if it's impossible for most to sustain today. Maybe that's part of God's saying in the life-to-come men and women will be as angels.
S-tier observation

Non-participation is the closest position to objectivity, the external perspective. It's why childless people often give good advice on children, why monks and saints in the wilderness provide better social commentary than sociologists, why Dr. Ray Peat called himself "a critic".

Also why Borges said a reader is always superior to the writer, because he never makes mistakes, his act is always perfect, an author always says too little or too much, but a reader always reads the perfect amount. He was puzzled why people were not content being "just" readers.
Counterpoint: Theodore Roosevelt's "The Man in the Arena" speech.
